          </table>
          <figcaption class="image-caption" style="box-sizing: content-box; color: #808080; font-size: 14px; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: -.15px; line-height: 20px; margin-top: 8px; padding-left: 15%; padding-right: 15%; text-align: center; width: 70%;">
           <em>
            Ezra Reporter AI
           </em>
          </figcaption>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Way before the launch of ChatGPT, Ezra had manually compiled a database of over 5,000 findings to train their AI model. Now, the model automatically compiles a report based off of the scans and radiologist readings, and sends the report to medical professionals who tweak and approve them. It takes what used to be a manual, 90 minute process down to five minutes, and means that Ezra can deliver reports to members in 3-5 days instead of 7-10 days.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Ezra Reporter helps bring down time spent by medical professionals, which lowers costs for consumers and, crucially, reduces the time spent waiting for results.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          Taken together, Ezra\xe2\x80\x99s suite of AI products means faster, cheaper, more accurate, more actionable, and more understandable scans and readings. By unlocking supply (30-minute scans means that twice as many people can get screened at every facility), they should create more demand for screens, help radiologists manage the increased volume,
         </span>
         <em>
          and
         </em>
         <span>
          support the company\xe2\x80\x99s internal medical providers in spinning out reports. Induced demand, and the tools to handle it.
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         All of the technology, however, is in service of the screening experience and results.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         To make it more concrete, I\xe2\x80\x99ll share my experience with Ezra. Turns out, the hardest part of the whole thing was confronting my mortality and deciding to do the scan in the first place.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <strong>
          Confronting Cancer
         </strong>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         It\xe2\x80\x99s not good, I know, but I have not been to the doctor for a checkup since I moved to New York in 2009.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         On the one hand, if a disease falls in my body and no doctor is there to see it\xe2\x80\xa6 all good, right?
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         On the other, there\xe2\x80\x99s a little bit of existential dread that slowly accumulates over time. The longer I don\xe2\x80\x99t go to the doctor, the less I want to go to the doctor, because the more I think there\xe2\x80\x99s likely to be something wrong when I do.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          When I\xe2\x80\x99ve allowed my brain to go there over the years, I viewed myself as a kind of Schr\xc3\xb6dinger's cat: neither healthy nor unhealthy, or both healthy
         </span>
         <em>
          and
         </em>
         <span>
          unhealthy, until an observer observes.
         </span>
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;">
         <figure style="margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" data-component-name="Image2ToDOMStatic" style="mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="908">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff7043987-ebe0-4fc9-86f5-d245df26eeb1_908x580.png" rel="" style="align-items: center; border: none; display: block; flex-direction: column; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; position: relative; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="wide-image" data-attrs='{"src":"https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f7043987-ebe0-4fc9-86f5-d245df26eeb1_908x580.png","fullscreen":null,"imageSize":null,"height":580,"width":908,"resizeWidth":null,"bytes":null,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":null,"href":null,"belowTheFold":true,"topImage":false,"internalRedirect":null}' height="351.3215859030837" src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1816,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff7043987-ebe0-4fc9-86f5-d245df26eeb1_908x580.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 100% !important; vertical-align: middle; width: auto !important;" width="550"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         I\xe2\x80\x99d still have no idea what was going on in there if it weren\xe2\x80\x99t for this newsletter.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          A couple of years ago, I signed up for
         </span>
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/37df81e2-ca62-45e6-8291-d140a94ba6f2?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">
          Fount
         </a>
         <span>
          because a) I wanted to get my energy back, and b) I needed to do the program if I was going to
         </span>
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/69bc3961-f293-4b81-8819-154183df81a1?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">
          write about it
         </a>
         <span>
          . I was excited about the whole thing \xe2\x80\x93 the blue light glasses, the Oura ring, the diet and meditation, the workouts \xe2\x80\x93 except for one part: the blood test. At the beginning of the program, and every 5 weeks thereafter, I\xe2\x80\x99d need to get my blood drawn so that the Fount team could understand what was happening in my body and personalize my plan. That part worried me.
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         I wasn\xe2\x80\x99t worried about the needles; I was worried that the results would come back and I\xe2\x80\x99d hop on a call with my coach, who would tell me, \xe2\x80\x9cI\xe2\x80\x99m really sorry but it\xe2\x80\x99s just a bunch of gerbils running around in there,\xe2\x80\x9d or something, \xe2\x80\x9cWhen\xe2\x80\x99s the last time you went to a doctor?\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Turns out, I was mostly fine, but the test discovered that I was anemic, among other minor things. Over the next few months, we fixed the anemia. I ended up with a bunch more hemoglobin and a little more peace of mind.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Not full peace of mind, though. Back in high school, when I ran cross country and track and therefore couldn\xe2\x80\x99t smoke cigarettes with the cool kids, I dipped with the other runners who couldn\xe2\x80\x99t smoke cigarettes with the cool kids. After practice, we\xe2\x80\x99d drive around and crack open a can of Skoal; on Friday nights, we\xe2\x80\x99d go to the movies and indulge in popcorn, soda, and Skoal.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         I noticed little bumps in my mouth then, but I was young and invincible and thought they\xe2\x80\x99d just go away. Another lifetime later, they\xe2\x80\x99re still there, and with them, a little nagging voice in my head that maybe they\xe2\x80\x99re cancer. Every time I run my tongue across the inside of the bottom of my mouth, part of my brain flashes a little image of me in jaw-removal surgery. That image has been there for a long time, and I\xe2\x80\x99ve gotten used to it, but when I had kids, it became particularly scary. What if my kids had to grow up without a dad because of some youthful tobacco indulgence? What if I couldn\xe2\x80\x99t see them grow up?
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          But of course, that thought was too terrifying to confront, so I just kind of shoved it into the depths of my brain as hard as I could and hoped for the best. Then, a few months ago, Fount\xe2\x80\x99s CEO,
         </span>
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/60463e70-1628-46b5-b94d-af5506451726?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">
          Andrew Herr
         </a>
         <span>
          , introduced me to
         </span>
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/57da5511-4022-4cf6-bea3-deebeba792d7?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">
          Emi
         </a>
         <span>
          . Emi was interested in a Not Boring piece about Ezra, and Andrew (
         </span>
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/6cab2300-4dd7-4a7b-80b2-78af8c9a0526?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">
          my health guru
         </a>
         <span>
          ) was a proponent of the product, so we chatted.
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          As I learned more about Emi\xe2\x80\x99s story and about Ezra, about all the things you\xe2\x80\x99re reading about in this piece, I knew it was a story I wanted to tell. It\xe2\x80\x99s not often I have a chance to save lives with a Deep Dive. But that also meant something pretty uncomfortable:
         </span>
         <strong>
          I\xe2\x80\x99d need to confront that lingering fear and get a cancer scan.
         </strong>
         <span>
         </span>
        </p>
        <h3 class="header-with-anchor-widget" style="-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: #404040; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;">
         <strong>
          My Ezra Experience
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          Booking the scan is easy. I went to the
         </span>
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/3fda8272-9e28-4c05-8f5b-b0c0853c019e?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">
          Ezra site
         </a>
         <span>
          and picked a location, date, and time.
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Then I waited.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         The waiting was hard. The two weeks between booking and scanning felt longer than a normal two weeks. Those quiet fears got a little louder. Like an unwitting Stoic, I had to confront death in the early morning and late night hours when I didn\xe2\x80\x99t have other things to occupy my mind.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          In preparation, I took
         </span>
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/21270f17-3ae6-4510-909d-942956732ac2?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">
          Ezra\xe2\x80\x99s Risk Assessment
         </a>
         <span>
          , a 5-minute quiz based on the Harvard Cancer Risk Index, to gauge my pre-test probability of having cancer. Whether or not you get scanned, I recommend taking the assessment: it\xe2\x80\x99s useful to know your risk level, and the questionnaire serves as a good checklist of things to do and not to do.
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         I definitely eat processed meats more than 3 times per week, for example, and should probably stop doing that\xe2\x80\xa6
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;">
         <figure style="margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" data-component-name="Image2ToDOMStatic" style="mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
